String functions.

Spark gives you a full set of vectorized string operations, all running natively on the java virtual machine, so they are fast even across billions of rows.

The basics are what you would expect. Upper and lower change case. Trim, and its left and right variants, strip whitespace. Length gives you the character count. And substring extracts a slice by position, remembering that the position is one-based, not zero-based.

For combining strings, there are two tools. Concatenate joins values end to end. Concatenate-with-separator does the same but inserts a separator between each piece — perfect for building a slug or a display label out of several columns.

Then there is the regular-expression family, which is where the real power is. Split breaks a string into an array on a pattern. Regex-replace swaps matches for a replacement, so you can turn runs of whitespace into underscores. And regex-extract pulls out a specific capture group from a match, which lets you lift a structured piece out of messy text in a single expression.

The instinct to build — reach for these before you ever consider a custom function, because a regex one-liner here beats a slow Python round trip every time.
